\section*{Complete space of random variables}

\begin{itemize}
\item Remimber that aproach to random variables, that I promissed not
to mention?  Ok, here is another story from it.
\item Current story: $\Omega, {\cal F}, P$ and then ${\cal X} = \{X:$
such that X is a ${\cal F}$ measurable fuction on $\Omega\}$.
\item Alternative story, ${\cal X}$ is a set of random variables
\begin{itemize}
\item Define $E()$ as linear
\item Not very interesting--all you can do is add stuff up and convert
to new units
\item Would like to take $\sin()$, $\log()$, etc.
\item Cool fact: All interesting functions can be approximated by
polynomials.  Stone-Weierstrass theorem.
\item But a polynomial is just ``sums'' and ``times'' of random variables
\item So to talk about a polynomial we already know how to talk about
sums, we need to add ``times''
\item If $X$, $Y$ are random variables, we add $XY$ to our list of
random variables
\item But we need to be able to talk about $E()$ still.  So, we have
to talke about $E(XY)$.  If we can do this, we can do anything.  Why?
\item $Y = X^2 = XX$, so $Z = X^3 = XY$, so $X^4 = XY$ and $X^5 = YZ$,
etc.
\item So if we can do $E(XY)$ we are golden!  This is what we will
consider today.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{Variance}
\begin{itemize}
\item Easy definition $V(X) = \sum_x (x - E(X))^2 P(X=x)$
\item Pretty defn: $V(X) = E((X- E(X))^2)$
\end{itemize}

